<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Thorax: Anepimeron setose, other pleural sclerites asetose. Wing length (from arculus to apex): 
<quantity box="[375,516,324,350]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="2.4" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.3">2.3–2.5 mm</quantity>
in male (
<emphasis box="[628,643,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5); 
<quantity box="[714,855,324,350]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="2.4" valueMax="2.9" valueMin="1.9">1.9–2.9 mm</quantity>
in female (
<emphasis box="[989,1004,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5). First tarsomeres with apical spur 
<quantity box="[399,585,364,390]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.0275" valueMax="0.03" valueMin="0.025">0.025–0.03 mm</quantity>
long in male (
<emphasis box="[755,770,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5), 
<quantity box="[840,959,364,390]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.035">0.035 mm</quantity>
in female (
<emphasis box="[1092,1107,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 2). Tarsal claws simple, robust and strongly curved near midlength, similar in shape on 3 pairs of legs; empodia well developed, as long as bend in claws (
<figureCitation box="[864,935,444,470]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="2.[264,382,1798,1822]" captionTargetBox="[280,1298,389,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-56@2.[261,1326,369,1772]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 1. Male head (frontal). 2. Female head (frontal). 3. Male antennal flagellomeres 9­12. 4. Male antennal flagellomere 5. 5. Female antennal flagellomere 5. 6. Female, midtarsal claw and empodium (lateral)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051079" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051079/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Abdomen. Male (
<figureCitation box="[529,608,484,510]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1784,1808]" captionTargetBox="[444,1124,715,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[423,1163,700,1759]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 7. Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 8. Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 9. Male terminalia (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
): tergites 1–7 rectangular with complete row of posterior setae, several lateral setae, 2 basal trichoid sensilla and elsewhere with scattered scales. Tergite 8 constricted mesally with only 2 trichoid sensilla as vestiture. Sternites 2–7 rectangular with setae more abundant at midlength, complete row of posterior setae and 2 basal trichoid sensilla; sternite 8 ovoid with several scattered setae and 2 basal trichoid sensilla. Female (
<figureCitation box="[472,545,684,710]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1784,1808]" captionTargetBox="[444,1124,715,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[423,1163,700,1759]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 7. Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 8. Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 9. Male terminalia (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
): tergites 1–7 as in male. Tergite 8 notched laterally with 2 basal trichoid sensilla. Sternites 2–6 as in male. Sternite 7 with scattered setae and 2 basal trichoid sensilla. Sternite 8 not sclerotized.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[520,595,804,830]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1784,1808]" captionTargetBox="[444,1124,715,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[423,1163,700,1759]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 7. Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 8. Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 9. Male terminalia (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
): gonocoxites wide and setose; gonostylus short, ovoid, and setose, with 2 sclerotized teeth; cercus reniform, completely separate and setose; hypoproct sligthly bilobed and setose; parameres absent; aedeagus triangular, tapering gradually toward apex, pointed apically.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
Ovipositor (
<figureCitation box="[453,523,964,990]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="3.[264,382,1784,1808]" captionTargetBox="[444,1124,715,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-164@3.[423,1163,700,1759]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 7. Male abdominal segment 3 to end (dorsolateral). 8. Female abdominal segment 5 to end (dorsolateral). 9. Male terminalia (dorsal)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051083/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) protrusible and needlelike, needle part 1.7–2.2 as long as sternite 7 (
<emphasis box="[274,289,1004,1029]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 4).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,384,1044,1070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Pupa.</emphasis>
Color: brownish. Length: 
<quantity box="[702,859,1044,1070]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8249999999999997" metricValueMax="4.1" metricValueMin="3.55" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="3.8249999999999997" valueMax="4.1" valueMin="3.55">3.55–4.1 mm</quantity>
(
<emphasis box="[878,893,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5). Head (
<figureCitation box="[1048,1137,1044,1070]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
): antennal horn triangular, long (
<quantity box="[460,635,1084,1110]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.195" valueMax="0.23" valueMin="0.16">0.16–0.23 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis box="[648,663,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5), with serrated margin; cephalic seta 
<quantity box="[1152,1323,1084,1110]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="7" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.055" valueMax="0.07" valueMin="0.04">0.04–0.07 mm</quantity>
long (
<emphasis box="[337,352,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5); upper frontal horns bilobed (length: 
<quantity box="[878,989,1124,1150]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.01">0.01 mm</quantity>
, 
<emphasis box="[1005,1020,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5); lower frontal horn absent; 2 pairs of lower facial papillae (1 pair asetose, other pair with seta 
<quantity box="[1151,1323,1164,1190]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.015" valueMax="0.02" valueMin="0.01">0.01–0.02 mm</quantity>
long, 
<emphasis box="[332,347,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5); 3 pairs of lateral facial papillae (1 pair with seta 
<quantity box="[1002,1188,1204,1230]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.0175" valueMax="0.02" valueMin="0.015">0.015–0.02 mm</quantity>
long and 2 pairs asetose). Upper cephalic margin thickened laterally. Thorax: prothoracic spiracle setiform, elongate and curved, 
<quantity box="[633,804,1284,1310]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7999999999999998" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="0.18" valueMax="0.2" valueMin="0.16">0.16–0.20 mm</quantity>
long (
<emphasis box="[884,899,1284,1309]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5) (
<figureCitation box="[975,1063,1284,1310]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1308,1284,1310]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
): segments 2–9 with transverse rows of crescent dorsal spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,395,1364,1390]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Larva.</emphasis>
Body elongate, cylindrical, and tapered at both ends. Color: yellow. Length: 
<quantity box="[264,406,1404,1430]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" unit="mm" value="2.2" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="1.8">1.8–2.6 mm</quantity>
(
<emphasis box="[423,438,1404,1429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">n</emphasis>
= 5). Integument rough. Spatula with 2 well developed teeth and relatively short stalk; surrounding area not pigmented; sternal papillae setose; 4 setose lateral papillae on each side of spatula (
<figureCitation box="[654,734,1484,1510]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig.13</figureCitation>
). Terminal segment short, convex, with 4 pairs of terminal papillae (
<figureCitation box="[478,565,1524,1550]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–14" captionStartId="5.[264,382,1806,1830]" captionTargetBox="[305,1269,400,1759]" captionTargetId="figure-76@5.[289,1277,393,1772]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–14. Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. 10. Pupal head (frontal). 11. Pupal prothoracic spiracle. 12. Pupal terminal segments (dorsal). 13. Larval spatula and associated papillae. 14. Larval terminal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051085" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051085/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1325,284,1870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,365,1564,1590]" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Gall</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[382,470,1564,1590]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="6.[264,368,1305,1329]" captionTargetBox="[281,1305,633,1294]" captionTargetId="figure-239@6.[281,1305,632,1296]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 15. Gall of Asphondylia microcapillata sp. n. on Bauhinia brevipes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5051089" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5051089/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). The spheroid leaf galls are covered with short, whitish trichomes. The gall is positioned between the adaxial leaf laminae and has a single chamber where a single galling larva is found. The two polar regions of the spheroid galls collapse the twolobed leaves of 
<emphasis box="[455,678,1684,1709]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName box="[455,674,1684,1709]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Bauhinia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="4" pageNumber="31" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brevipes">Bauhinia brevipes</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
At the beginning of gall formation, the trichomes are whitish but may change color as the galls mature, and when exposed to direct sunlight may present reddish tones at the distal portion of the trichomes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
